      "role": "user",
      "content": "the sinkhole metaphor makes sense i guess but it feels like there's something more going on. like i'm paying extra for stuff i didnt sign up for. are there like hidden fees or something that just eat the payment before it even touches the principal?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're onto something there. There are indeed some hidden fees and charges that can eat into your payment, making it seem like the principal isn't decreasing as much as you'd like. These fees can be sneaky, but they're like the little goblins that live in the sinkhole, nibbling away at your payment before it even reaches the principal.\n\nOne common culprit is the \"origination fee\", which is a one-time charge that's added to the loan when it's first disbursed. It's like a tiny goblin that attaches itself to your loan and starts siphoning off a small amount of money every month. Origination fees can range from 1% to 4% of the loan amount, and they can add up quickly.\n\nAnother fee to watch out for is the \"late payment fee\", which can be charged if you miss a payment. It's like a pesky little goblin that shows up uninvited and starts demanding payment. Late payment fees can be steep, and they can really eat into your payment.\n\nAnd then there's the \"accrued interest\", which is the interest that's charged on the outstanding balance, even if you're making payments on time. It's like the sinkhole",
